🔷 4. CONTROLLER ENGINE — SYSTEM GOVERNOR

The Controller Engine is the most critical layer in your frontend system.

🔑 Core Responsibilities
1. State Ownership
holds server snapshot
holds local draft state
tracks dirty state
2. Execution Control
decides when save is allowed
triggers mutations
prevents invalid execution
3. Reconciliation
replaces state with server snapshot
prevents overwrites when dirty
resolves conflicts
4. Workflow Coordination
triggers async workflows
polls worker status
refreshes on completion
5. Section Isolation
each section operates independently
each section has its own lifecycle
🔥 Critical Rule

No system behavior exists outside the controller

🔷 5. CONTROLLER ARCHITECTURE (ENGINE STRUCTURE)
🧩 Hierarchical Controllers
RecordController
  → SectionController
      → ItemController
          → AllocationController
🎮 1. Record Controller
Responsibilities
loads full record snapshot
initializes all sections
coordinates global refresh
manages record-level state
🎮 2. Section Controller (PRIMARY UNIT)
Responsibilities
owns section draft
tracks dirty state
exposes:
save()
discard()
reconcile()
triggerWorkflow()
handles:
section-level validation state
section-level errors
🔑 Rule

🔥 Section is the primary execution unit

(aligns with your system design)

🎮 3. Item Controller
Responsibilities
manages item-level state
syncs with section controller
tracks item-level changes
🎮 4. Allocation Controller
Responsibilities
manages allocation rows
validates against inventory (UI-level constraints only)
updates item aggregates
🔷 6. DRAFT & SNAPSHOT MODEL

The controller maintains two states:

🧠 Server Snapshot (Source of Truth)
last known server state
immutable reference
✏️ Draft State
user-modified state
mutable
marked as dirty
🔁 Dirty Tracking
if draft !== snapshot → dirty = true
🔑 Rule

🔥 Draft is temporary — snapshot is truth

🔷 7. SAVING SYSTEM (CONTROLLED BY CONTROLLER)
Flow
User clicks Save
→ Controller validates state
→ Controller sends mutation
→ Server returns snapshot
→ Controller replaces state
→ dirty = false
Critical Rule

❗ Controller NEVER merges — it REPLACES state

This enforces:

consistency
correctness
no drift
🔷 8. RECONCILIATION SYSTEM (CONTROLLER CORE)

The controller ensures UI is always aligned with server.

Behavior Matrix
State	Controller Behavior
Clean	Auto refresh
Dirty	Block overwrite
Worker complete	Force refresh

👉 This matches your system-wide reconciliation model

Responsibilities
detect stale data
trigger refresh
prevent data loss
🔷 9. WORKFLOW GOVERNANCE

Controller governs all async execution.

Flow
Controller triggers workflow
→ API call
→ Worker processes
→ Controller polls
→ On completion:
    → refresh snapshot
Responsibilities
track workflow status
prevent duplicate triggers
update UI state
🔷 10. ERROR HANDLING (CONTROLLER → UI)
Flow
Transport → Controller → UI
Responsibilities
map errors to section scope
attach errors to correct controller
expose to UI
Rule

❗ Errors must always resolve to a section or action

🔷 11. ENGINE GOVERNANCE RULES (NON-NEGOTIABLE)
1. No Direct API Calls from UI
all calls go through controller
2. No Business Logic in Controller
controller orchestrates — does not decide rules
3. No Partial State Updates
always replace with snapshot
4. Section Isolation
each section fully independent
5. Controller Owns Lifecycle
mount → load → edit → save → reconcile
6. Shared Controllers Only
no feature-specific controller logic
7. UI is Replaceable
controller logic must survive UI changes
🔷 12. SHARED ENGINE (REUSABILITY MODEL)

